## `git-id` alias

Sets your commit authorship on the current repo.

```bash
git-id
# Git identity set: dannySubsense <danny@subsense.art>
```

- Defined in `~/.bash_aliases`
- Loads automatically on every new terminal
- Run once inside any repo after clone or init
- Verify anytime: `git config --list | grep user`

---

## Tokens — PAT vs `gh` OAuth token

| | PAT (Personal Access Token) | `gh` OAuth token |
|---|---|---|
| What it is | Generated manually in GitHub Settings | Created automatically when you run `gh auth login` |
| Stability | Stable until you revoke it or it expires | Can rotate when `gh` refreshes its session |
| Get it | GitHub → Settings → Developer Settings → Personal Access Tokens → Tokens (classic) | `gh auth token` |
| Best used for | `.env` files, URL overrides, anywhere stable auth is needed | One-off `gh` CLI commands |

**Always use a PAT for `.env` files and URL overrides.** Using the `gh` OAuth token will silently break when the session rotates.

Generate a PAT at: `https://github.com/settings/tokens`
- Token type: **Tokens (classic)**
- Scope: **repo** (full repo access is sufficient)
- Expiry: 90 days is a reasonable default

